<p>In <a href="/wiki/Behavioral_economics" title="Behavioral economics">behavioral economics</a>, <b>hyperbolic discounting</b> refers to the <a href="/wiki/Empirical" title="Empirical">empirical</a> finding that people generally prefer smaller, sooner payoffs to larger, later payoffs when the smaller payoffs would be imminent. However, when the same payoffs are distant in time,<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> people tend to prefer the larger outcome, even though the time lag from the smaller to the larger would be the same as before.</p>
